<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Environment, Food and Rural Affairs Committee Inquiry into Food Security</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-size:13pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:center"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Cambria; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Submission by the Food Ethics Council</span></h2><h3 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></h3><h3 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></h3><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Food Ethics Council is a charity that provides independent advice on the ethics of food and farming. Our aim is to create</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a food system that is fair and healthy for people and the environment. In pursuit of this aim, we:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Research and analyse ethical issues</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Mediate between stakeholders</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Develop tools for ethical decision-making</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Act as honest brokers in policy and public de</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bate.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2. The 14</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> members of the Food Ethics Council are all leaders in their relevant fields, and appointed as individuals. They bring a broad range of expertise to our work, from academic research through to practical knowledge of farming, business and po</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">licy.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary of main points</span></h3><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UK and EU food security cannot be considered in isolation from global food security</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The central priority for success</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ful</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> efforts to reduce hunger and improve food security must be to tackle the social injustice that pervades all aspects of the food system.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Food prices do not currently reflect the full social and environmental costs of food production and consumption</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> necessary, and possible, to rectify this imbalance without exacerbating the already significant problem of UK food poverty.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Regarding science and GM technology, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">we think that it would be more helpful for the committee to address the broader question abou</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t 'The potential value and contribution of science to UK food security' separately from any discussion of one specific application of knowledge arising from that science such as GM food and feed.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Climate change risks are not adequately incorporated within</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> UK food security strategies and planning.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he fundamental problem for small farmers is that power imbalances mean they cannot get a fair price for their produce</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This adversely impacts upon</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> food security in a number of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ways.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></h3><h3 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></h3><h3 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How best to improve UK (and </span><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">EU) food security, including u</span><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">sing resources more efficiently</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Future UK and EU food security cannot be considered in isolation from global food security</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is essential, therefore, that this EFRA committee inquiry takes full account of the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">report and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">recommendations of the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> inquiry into Global Food Security that was conducted by the International Development Committee </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(‘IDC’) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">earlier this year</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The main points from the Food Ethics Council’s submission to the IDC inquiry were summarised as follows:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">central priority for successful efforts to reduce hunger and improve food security must be to tackle the social injustice that pervades all aspects of the food system.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-indent:1.5pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The governance of agricultural research needs to be revised to ensure that small-scale </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">producers have a fair say in decisions on priorities that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> will shape their opportunities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for years to come.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-indent:1.5pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is a sufficient body of evidence on the relationship between food price volatility and speculation on food commodities to warrant further </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">regulation of that speculation.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We would particularly stress the first of the above points, which applies equally to domestic and global food security, and underpins the Food Ethics Council’s approach to the question of food security. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The world current</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ly produces more than enough food to feed the population, but around a billion people are still living in hunger</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This doesn’t mean that measures to increase food production and productivity have no place in addressing global food insecurity – they clearly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> do – but it does mean that the central priority for successful efforts to reduce hunger and improve food security must be to tackle inequality.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5. In the UK context, this means that levels of social security benefits, and of wages, need to be high enough</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to enable all members of society to afford healthy, sustainable diet</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">6. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">One of the most glaring inefficiencies of resource use is using crops that could be used to feed people to feed animals instead</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This is not only a grossly inefficient way of provi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ding people with the protein they need, it is also a major factor in the adverse environmental impact of today’s food system.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> However, we recognise that livestock farming and meat eating (in moderation) can deliver benefits, which is why we advocate ‘less </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and better’ meat consumption.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The relationship between the price of food and the cost of producing </span><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">it</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is widely recognised that food prices do not currently reflect the full social and environmental costs of food production and consumption</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> generally seen as creating an impossible dilemma for policy-makers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">On the one hand, we surely cannot continue to ignore the massive, and increasing,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> cost to the NHS of dealing with diet-related illness (for example); or,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to take another example</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> from the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">environmental perspective, the cost of dealing with the pollution of our water system as a result of current approaches to agricultural production</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">On the other hand, however, we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">already have a very serious problem of food security among the UK population,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> so any measure that might exacerbate that problem – such as pushing up food prices so that they reflect these wider social and environmental costs – seems an equally untenable option.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">8. We suggest that there are two </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">considerations that point the way tow</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ards resolving this dilemma:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">First, it should not be automatically assumed that consumers should be the ones who have to absorb these external costs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Why should it not be the individuals and organisations who currently make substantial financial gains fro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">m producing, manufacturing and selling the food products that give rise to these external cost</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">?</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Hence, the Food Ethics Council supports the ‘polluter pays’ principle.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Second, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">it is crucial to recognise </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">these wider social and environmental costs are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">– by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">definition</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> – </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">primarily </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">associated with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">unhealthy, u</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nsustainably produced food</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This means that, to the extent that food prices do come to reflect these wider costs, the cost of healthy, sustainably produced food will actually fall relative to unhealthy, un</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sustainably produced food</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For this reason, the Food Ethics Council supports measures such as the introduction of a ‘sugary drinks </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">duty</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as a means of ensuring the relative prices of healthy and unhealthy food reflect these wider costs. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The potential valu</span><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">e and contribution of science and GM</span><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> technology to UK food security</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">9. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The first point that we would make on this issue is that we do</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">not feel that this question is well framed by linking science to GM technology directly, and that it therefore risks intr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oducing an unhelpfully narrow focus into the committee’s deliberations. We think that it would be more helpful for the committee to address the broader question about 'The potential value and contribution of science to UK food security' separately from any</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> discussion of one specific application of knowledge arising from that science such as GM food and feed.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">10. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In debates about different ways of delivering food security, GM food and feed is often considered. At the Food Ethics Council, we are open to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">exploring a range of options that move us towards a world where all eat healthily and sustainably, enjoying food that is produced and traded fairly and humanely. However, we think it is essential that GM is not regarded as 'the default option', whereby the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> discussion focuses exclusively on the merits or demerits of GM food and feed. There are many other areas of science around soils and agronomy, for example, that may be equally important for underpinning sustainable food production systems, but which are g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">iven much less attention than we believe they merit.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">11. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In exploring the potential contribution of different technologies, our view is that there is no such thing as a ‘good technology’ or a ‘bad technology’. It is the application of the technology, rath</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">er than the technology itself, that should be of concern. In considering different technologies, we believe it is important to address questions such as (i) who has or will have what power and control over the technologies developed and (ii) who gets the b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">enefits and who carries the risks from the technologies being used – or to put it another way, who does the technology empower and disempower?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">12. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In relation to food and agricultural research more broadly (including more specifically in relation to novel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> technologies), we feel it is essential that we have a strong publicly funded research effort to balance and complement commercial sector research.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">13. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">On the general question of the potential value and contribution of science in relation to food security</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">we think that science has a considerable role to play. In noting that, we should also recognize that there are other important factors that contribute to food security (or insecurity). These include geo-political shifts, the way governments and societies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> respond to the growing pressures brought about by the need to adapt to the effects of climate destabilisation, competition for resources and growing inequality – all of which could disrupt existing trading patterns, supply chains, growing conditions and l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ead to conflicts. Science has a role in providing greater understanding of how to respond to these but gives no guarantee that we have the wisdom to choose to do the right thing with that knowledge. Here much depends on the research agenda being pursued an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d the key questions that should be asked of any technological application of the increasing knowledge arising from human endeavour.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Whether climate change risks are adequately incorporated in UK food s</span><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ecurity strategies and planning</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">14. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In short, no. Th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ere are a number of reasons why climate change risks should be better incorporated into UK food security strategies and planning, which include:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is those areas that can least cope with it that are likely to be worst affected by the physical impacts of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">climate change (for example in sub-Saharan Africa).</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As well as the moral argument for the UK to help, there is also a strong economic argument. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">severe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">security of supply risks to UK businesses sourcing from the Global South – </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as well as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> associate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d investor risks. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This should not just be about minimising future impacts and/ or about passively preparing for the inevitable changes that climate change will bring. There are lots of opportunities (and potential economic benefits) for the UK to proacti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">vely lead the way in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">adically decarbonising our economy – and in doing so to strongly promote energy efficiency and the use of</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> appropriate renewable energy.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is a strong social justice argument that those countries that have been responsible for pro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ducing significant levels of greenhouse gas emissions historically (hence the UK is an important player) should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">recognise that responsibility.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The obstacles facing food producers, including small farmers, seeking to increase production and access new </span><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">market</span><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">s</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">15. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">On the basis of the Food Ethics Council’s recent work, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">fu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ndamental problem</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for small farmers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is that power imbalances mean they can</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">no</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t get a fair price for their produce</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This adversely impacts </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">up</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> food security in the following </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ways:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Small farmers </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">driven out of business</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Potential new entrants are discouraged.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Farmers cannot </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">make longer-term investments in more sustainable production.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">16. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Other obstacles facing small farmers include:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Lack of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the necessary</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> infrastructure (throug</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">h the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">closure of abattoirs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, for example</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">).</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Lack of access to financial support (in the form of low-interest loans, for example)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>